30004985@@@@@@EyeBreak@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1391@LMC@2019-06-14
30004986@@@@@@Background@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1392@LMC@2019-06-14
30004987@@@@@@Singapore is ranked globally amongst the top for having high prevalence of myopia.@@@@1@13@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1393@LMC@2019-06-14
30004988@@@@@@Up to 65% of children aged 12 contracted myopia as compared to 12% in Australia and 30% in UK of the same age group.@@@@1@24@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1394@LMC@2019-06-14
30004989@@@@@@[1][2]@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1395@LMC@2019-06-14
30004990@@@@@@Problem@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1396@LMC@2019-06-14
30004991@@@@@@Scientific evidence indicate that myopia is caused by a mix of genetic and lifestyle factors.@@@@1@15@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1397@LMC@2019-06-14
30004992@@@@@@The lifestyle factors to myopia include long hours of near work such as reading and writing, computer use and lack of outdoor activity time.@@@@1@24@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1398@LMC@2019-06-14
30004993@@@@@@Heavy use of computers by children can lead to higher risk of developing and worsening myopic conditions at a small age.@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1399@LMC@2019-06-14
30004994@@@@@@[3]@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1400@LMC@2019-06-14
30004995@@@@@@The lack of cure to myopia means that preventive measures must be taken to encourage people cultivate good eye care habits.@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:174; ntucle-sid:1401@LMC@2019-06-14
